{
  "text": "Indications for immediate cystectomy in T1Hg disease do exist. They include extensive unresectable disease, diverticular disease, associated hydronephrosis, lymphovascular invasion, prostatic stromal or ductal involvement or variant histology (squamous cell, adenocarcinoma, micropapillary, small cells that require chemotherapy first). Some patients with T1Hg disease and with no concomitant CIS may be candidates for partial cystectomy. Relative indications for cystectomy include multifocal disease, associated CIS, T1 disease on repeat resection, deep T1 disease abutting the muscle and poor patient compliance. The presence of tumours that are greater than 3 cm, their multifocality and the presence of CIS have been reported as negatively prognostic. [CITATION_1] ",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "12302638"
